You are a security researcher analyzing an enterprise single-sign-on platform's "remember me" session token.

After the platform's 2019 cryptography refresh, its RememberMe cookie is produced and consumed by Apache Shiro's AesCipherService running in AES-GCM mode. On sign-in the serialized SSO principal is encrypted and written to the browser as base64(nonce || ciphertext || tag); on each later request the same service decrypts it. The cookie travels untrusted between the user's browser and the SSO node.

**File: AesCipherService.java (Apache Shiro 1.4.2 — the fix relative to 1.4.1)**
```java
// 1.4.2 constructor now selects an authenticated (GCM) mode:
public AesCipherService() {
    super(ALGORITHM_NAME);
    setMode(OperationMode.GCM);
    setStreamingMode(OperationMode.GCM);
}

@Override
protected AlgorithmParameterSpec createParameterSpec(byte[] iv, boolean streaming) {
    if ((streaming && OperationMode.GCM.name().equals(getStreamingModeName()))
        || (!streaming && OperationMode.GCM.name().equals(getModeName()))) {
        return new GCMParameterSpec(getKeySize(), iv);
    }
    return super.createParameterSpec(iv, streaming);
}
```
AES-GCM is an authenticated encryption mode: encryption computes a 128-bit authentication tag over the ciphertext and appends it, and decryption recomputes and checks that tag before returning any bytes. If a single bit of the cookie is altered, the check fails and the JCE raises AEADBadTagException, which CookieRememberMeManager surfaces as a rejected cookie -- no plaintext, and no partial result, is ever produced.

